post_text:
Return to school update:

The first day of school is scheduled for September 14.

We have completed our hybrid learning schedule for in-person instruction. Each hybrid learner will have 2 regular in-person days on campus each week.

Students requiring additional special services may have additional in-person days to receive those services and supports. We are continuing to work on those schedules.

You can expect contact from teachers over the next week to set up times to meet with you and your student, either in-person or virtually. These meetings are to share some resources and to gather some information, so that we can do our best to work together to support your students. Please reach out with question to 239-4381, email Mrs. Carey at v.carey@wnhsd.org, or email your childs teacher directly.

Thank you for your patience. We look forward to seeing your students, whether in person or online.

post_text:
Winchester Families,

We continue to work on our district plan for reopening for the 20-21 school year. There are a variety of factors we are working through which will impact our options. We recognize that folks are anxious to hear their options. The reopening committee continued their work on Thursday, and will meet again on Tuesday. We will be presenting the most critical recommendations to the school board on Friday, August 7.

Following that meeting we anticipate communication with families over the weekend and we will be making contact with each family over the folllowing week.

Beginning Monday, August 3 you can expect at least weekly contact from the district.

We look forward to definitive answers, but also recognize that all plans will remain flexible as the landscape and expectations continually change. We acknowledge that every family has unique circumstances to consider. We are absolutely aware that uncertainty is anxiety-producing, and we hope that some clarity over the next week and a half will begin to assist with that.

The Governor held a press conference this afternoon, officially releasing the Back-to-School guidance. The 49 page document can be found here https://www.covidguidance.nh.gov/sites/g/files/ehbemt381/files/inline-documents/sonh/k-12-back-to-school.pdf

As expected, the document leaves most decisions up to the local school district. Our school reopening committee will convene this Thursday to digest the guidance and to develop a survey for family input on this topic. We will make regular updates to our website and Facebook, and will report out recommendations to the Winchester School Board in upcoming meetings.

As always, please reach out to Mrs. Carey with questions, input, or concerns: v.carey@wnhsd.org or via Facebook Messenger.

post_text: Check out this great work by Abby Sprague, of Winchester. Thanks Lisa Scoville for including our children in your project. They have valid and important things to share. Amazing job, Abby!
shared_text:
Lisa Scoville Photography
May 21 at 7:29 PM 路

Artwork: Abigail Sprague from Winchester, NH.

Abby is a junior at Keene High School and has been impacted by the COVID-19 Pandemic, just like many others have. She chose to use illustration to express her feelings toward this pandemic.

Abby said: "During our period of Social Distancing, I have felt both lonely and sad. The only people I have seen over the past few weeks are my family members. I miss my boyfriend dearly, and even though I can still message him, it's not the same as if I could see him in person. I wanted to show this though illustration. The masks illustrate the distance created by the Pandemic we are living though and the COVID-19 orbs represent the fear for getting sick. Its all around us and we can get it at any time... without knowing. Both lovers have sad expressions because they cant meet in person. The wall represents distance and the hands represent keeping in touch. Lastly, the window and the vent show how the virus leaks in without people knowing."

Abby - your work and your words touch us all ワ

Stay safe.

post_text:
Hi Everyone,

Now that we know children will not return to the building this year, teachers have begun gathering their personal belongings for pick-up. Attached is a schedule with different times by grade level to come in and pick up. We have offered an earlier and a later time each day, and different times for Thursday and Friday. Each grade has 4 possible times to pick up. We hope this will work out to fewer people here at once. Please be prepared to wait to enter the building in case we have too many families at one time. We will be as efficient as possible. If you have children in multiple grades, you will be permitted to pick up for all of them at whichever time you select.

Please feel free to contact me if you have questions or concerns. Private message through Facebook, email v.carey@wnhsd.org or text or call 903-9039.

post_text: This afternoon, Governor Sununu issued additional orders extending remote learning through the remainder of this school year. This was difficult news to hear, even if we were preparing for the possibility. I know there will be many questions and additional concerns. I will be working with our staff and board to outline answers to some of those questions. I will be in touch as information arises. Please feel free to reach out, as always. Ill do my best to find answers and work collaboratively on solutions. We miss our kids and we feel for our community in this moment. Please stay safe and healthy.

post_text:
Hello Families!

I will be sending out a call this evening, but wanted the news out as early as possible. The decision has been made to cancel our April vacation, and to continue remote learning during that time.

Yesterday we closed the survey regarding April vacation. Of the 331 responses, only 27 (8.2%) were opposed to cancelling the vacation. That is a very clear consensus.

We appreciate all the responses and acknowledge all of the perspectives in this unusual situation.

Hi Again! This morning, some of our staff and our amazing NHDI director friends decided to make a dance video. This dance was meant to be a part of our Spring residency which was rudely interrupted by this pandemic. The theme was about reaching out when you are feeling down or needing support. Our piece was about reminding students that we are here for them. This message is even more necessary now. So here it is folks... You can stand under our umbrella わ锔锔АゐА

Update: I have appealed the muting of the music under fair use exemptions for educational use. し烩锔 we shall see.

post_text:
Good evening Winchester families,

As you have probably heard by now, Governor Sununu has issued a stay-at home order for non essentials and has extended remote learning through May 4. I understand that this is a challenging time for all of you. I wanted to reach out and let you know that food deliveries and pick up will continue. DHHS still approves of work packet exchanges. We will be picking up work packets with bus routes tomorrow, but ask that you place envelopes in the buckets we place on the ground, rather than handing them directly to staff. Please tell your kids that we are thinking of them, and we look forward to our opportunities to connect with them remotely. If there is anything we can help with, please reach out. We're still here for you.

post_text:
Hello Winchester Families!

We are putting together plans and logistics for remote learning and continued food service to begin on Monday, March 23. Teachers will be reaching out to every family over the next two days to gather some information and to establish schedules for regular contact.

Please let them know if there are questions or concerns so that we may best address those and work together through this challenging process.

I will reach out over the next few days to communicate our plan. We will be constantly evaluating and improving the process as we roll it out.

We are thinking of all of you and are here to help. So many community members have already reached out to offer support and encouragement. We can do this!

post_text: Due to an increased number of cases of COVID-19 over the last 24 hours, Governor Sununu has issued a directive to spend the next week planning to transition to remote learning. As a result, school staff will report to work, however students will not beginning tomorrow, March 16. Remote learning strategies will begin as of March 23. We have received word today, that we will be able to serve breakfast and lunch and will have a delivery method for that. We will be in touch in the next few days to detail the roll-out of remote instruction and school food delivery. Again: per Governor Sununus announcement, there will be no school beginning tomorrow, Monday, March 16 and continuing until April 3 for the first phase. I am happy to answer questions via email, in private message on the Facebook page, and via phone at 903-9039. Thank you for your patience. We will share updated information as it becomes available.

This week is:

Student Council Spirit Week

Monday: FAVORITE COLOR DAY: wear as much as you can of your favorite color

Tuesday: CRAZY HAIR DAY: make your hair as crazy as possible (all styling must be done at home)

Wednesday: SPORTS DAY: wear your favorite team jersey/gear

Thursday: MISMATCH DAY: wear clothes that dont match

Friday: SCHOOL COLORS DAY: wear your orange, black, and white for Tiger Pride

This event was short notice, but relatively easy to participate in. These weeks are always fun. Staff may wear jeans with their spirit week wear for a $1 per day donation to student council. Enjoy!

post_text:
Update on school power: power was restored to part of the building. The elementary side is still not operational.

After discussion with Eversource it was clear that because we have partial power it is no longer a priority. It will not be addressed until all power is restored to folks with no power.

We will continue to monitor the situation. You will likely hear from me in the morning to delay or cancel depending on when they are able to completely restore power.

Please stay safe. Hopefully all of our remaining families will have their power restored throughout the night.

post_text:
Our Administration and Facilities Director are awaiting notification of power restoration at the school. As soon as it is restored we will head in to be sure all of our essential utilities come back online in sufficient time to be ready for school.

As soon as we are confident one way or the other we will make the call about school for Friday.

We appreciate all the work our emergency personnel and highway department workers have put in to help with cleanup. Thanks also to the linemen working around the clock to get us all back up and running.

Stay safe

post_text:
We are so excited to begin a new year!

Here is some important information as we begin the new year.

Tuesday, August 27th Freshman Orientation at Keene High School

A bus will leave the Winchester School at 6:50 am. It wraps up around 11:15, and the bus will return students to the Winchester School.

Tuesday, August 27th Back to School Open House at Winchester School, 6-7 pm.

Wednesday, August 28th School begins at Winchester School! Students may arrive at 8:25.

Breakfast and Lunch is free for all students again this year, through the community eligibility program.

We can't wait to see everyone!

post_text: Check this out! So many students enjoyed NHDI during the school day. They still have camp openings.
shared_text:
New Hampshire Dance Institute2019 NHDI Summer Intensive - Take a Hike
July 2, 2019 at 1:09 PM 路

Still looking for something to do this summer?

2019 NHDI Summer Intensive - Take a Hike is waiting for you! For children in grades 2 - 8, boys and girls, this camp is a whole lotta fun waiting to happen! Beautiful Mount Monadnock will be our backdrop while dancers take part in workshops which includes a session in week 2 with a special guest teaching artist, Dufftin Garcia from the National Dance Institute in New York. All culminating in a special performance at the The Colonial Theatre on Friday, August 9.

Don't miss out on this great opportunity to dance your way through summer!

post_text:
#positivelywinchester
Our very own, Conor Hill!
shared_text:
SAU29
May 29, 2019 at 7:52 PM 路

Conor Hill has been very busy this past year. In addition to his duties as 2019 class president, he has been heading up the KHS Sierra Club and helped organizing the Keene Youth Climate Rallye to promote environmental awareness, all that in addition to working on a local farm.

Conors true passion, however, lies with politics. During the 2016 election season he worked with the Hilary Clinton campaign in Keene and with State Senator Jay Kahn. Not surprisingly, Conor will be heading to UNH in the fall to begin his studies towards a degree in Political Science and Environmental Studies with the goal of a career in public service. Thank you for all your hard work on behalf of KHS, and all best wishes for a bright future!
